[
    {
        "content": "<p>On the nLab page about the Dold-Kan correspondence, the result is given as an equivalence between connective chain complexes and simplicial objects <em>in any abelian category</em> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. The given reference is a paper by Dold and Puppe, which unfortunately is in German.<br>\nDo you know a reference in English (or Spanish or Italian, for what matters)? Looking in the interweb I can only find expositions for the case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">b</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A = \\mathbf{Ab}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">b</span></span></span></span></span>.<br>\nIf not, could someone explain to me what's the nerve/realization adjunction in the general case? In particular, how's the 'standard cosimplicial object' of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> obtained?</p>",
        "id": 213164706,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602600005
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is Prop. 2.3 on that page not what you're looking for?</p>",
        "id": 213171103,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602602286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No that's for the case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">b</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A = \\mathbf{Ab}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">b</span></span></span></span></span>, not for a general abelian category</p>",
        "id": 213180663,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602605961
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It works as stated for any abelian category</p>",
        "id": 213181842,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602606431
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed, you're right for the realization functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Γ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Gamma</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span></span></span></span>, I didn't notice. But what about the nerve functor? It says to be just the Moore complex functor, though on the corresponding page only the case for simplicial groups is covered</p>",
        "id": 213182168,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602606591
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh yeah, it doesn't give a formula for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 213182320,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602606654
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But once you have a formula for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>, then you can just interpret it in any abelian category.</p>",
        "id": 213182402,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602606700
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Moore+complex#NormalizedChainComplexOnGeneralGroup\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Moore+complex#NormalizedChainComplexOnGeneralGroup</a></p>",
        "id": 213182497,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602606736
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For the \"joint kernel\", you can take the kernel of the map into the (finite) direct sum whose components are given by the various face maps.</p>",
        "id": 213182610,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602606793
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh right! I was too quick to dismiss that definition as not general enough</p>",
        "id": 213182826,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602606914
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks :)</p>",
        "id": 213182863,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602606934
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you want a less explicit description, then you can think of an arbitrary abelian category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> as a kind of module over {f.g. abelian groups}, so that you can tensor or cotensor an object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> by a f.g. abelian group. For this purpose, you'll only need the formulas <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z} \\otimes A = A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77222em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hom}(\\mathbb{Z}, A) = A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">H</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 213183094,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602607044
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then by extension you can also compute what the object of maps from a f.g. simplicial abelian group (in particular, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>k</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}[\\Delta^k]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.099108em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.849108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>) to a simplicial object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> should be, as an object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>; it will be given by some finite limit</p>",
        "id": 213183455,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602607206
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>er, I don't think this is quite the right example</p>",
        "id": 213183559,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602607267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>well, I'm getting confused by the presentation on the nLab but in the end the point is that the correspondence for Ab is given by some finite (co)limits, and we can interpret these equally well in any abelian category</p>",
        "id": 213183855,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602607442
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span> I was expecting a trick of this kind, though it's far from clear to me how to pull it off</p>",
        "id": 213184043,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602607531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's easy to get mixed up here because what would ordinarily be an adjunction in one direction is in fact an equivalence, and so also an adjunction in the other direction. As a result, both <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Γ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Gamma</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span></span></span></span> can be described using either limits or colimits.</p>",
        "id": 213185331,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602608140
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the case of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Γ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Gamma</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span></span></span></span> there is a finite direct sum = finite coproduct = finite product. In the case of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span>, IIRC, there's a canonical splitting that splits off the joint kernel of the d_i, so it can also be described as a quotient.</p>",
        "id": 213185539,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602608238
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the phrase \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Γ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Gamma</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Γ</span></span></span></span> are nerve and realization with respect to the cosimplicial chain complex\" I think <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is supposed to be the realization, so <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is being described as a colimit/coend.</p>",
        "id": 213185862,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602608393
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyways, what I wanted to say originally is that while the object that tells you how to turn a simplicial abelian group into a chain complex of abelian group is a cosimplicial chain complex, the object that tells you how to turn a simplicial object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> into a chain complex in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is also (or can be) a cosimplicial chain complex <em>of abelian groups</em>.</p>",
        "id": 213186132,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602608520
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is a general abelian category then it might not have infinite coproducts so we need some finiteness condition on the cosimplicial chain complex.</p>",
        "id": 213186227,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602608550
    }
]